ter of one of the important political debates in the late Middle Ages: how to constrain the king and allow for his subjects' participation. Fictions of Advice rereads the English mirrors for princes to show how their moralizing was often highly topical and even subversive. Although overtly deferential to the rulers they address, the mirrors' authors were surprisingly capable of criticism and opposition. In putting the texts back into their historical contexts, Ferster reveals the vital cultural and political function they fulfilled in their societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAuthors, EnglishyMiddle English, 1100-1500xPolitical and social views. 0aCivilization, Medieval, in literature. 0aDidactic literature, English (Middle)xHistory and criticism. 0aEducation of princes in literature. 0aKings and rulers in literature. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z97831104425260 cprintz978081223332240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280552940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512805529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781512805529.jpg  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK